<ns2076:section xmlns:ns2076="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.tecnologies.java.networking.eMail.javaMail">
    
    <ns2077:title xmlns:ns2077="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JavaMail</ns2077:title>

<ns2078:para xmlns:ns2078="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Of course you can write a e-mail applications using the Java's TCP/IP support
directly. That would, however, be quite cuimbersome. Effectively you would have 
to implement the low level mail protocols yourself. </ns2078:para>

<ns2079:para xmlns:ns2079="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Support for electronic mail
is now available for Java in the form of an add-on package which can be freely 
downloaded from <ns2080:emphasis xmlns:ns2080="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="verb">java.sun.com</ns2080:emphasis>. You will also have to download JAF, the
<ns2081:emphasis xmlns:ns2081="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Activation Framework</ns2081:emphasis>. Both, <ns2082:emphasis xmlns:ns2082="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="verb">mail.jar</ns2082:emphasis> and <ns2083:emphasis xmlns:ns2083="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" role="verb">activation.jar</ns2083:emphasis> 
must be included in your class path when using <ns2084:emphasis xmlns:ns2084="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JavaMail</ns2084:emphasis>.</ns2079:para>
    
